Durban - The situation at George Campbell School of Technology escalated on Friday morning as pupils continued protesting against teachers who apparently called them monkeys. Andreas Mathios, Blue Security community and media liaison officer, said police are in attendance and are controlling the situation. The protest had become violent and teachers were forced find ways to protect themselves and other pupils. “Teachers have locked themselves and pupils in classrooms and rioters are hammering and breaking doors,” said Mathios. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. WATCH: Racism uproar at Durban school continues. Video: Sithembile Mkhwanazi On Thursday George Campbell pupils told the Daily News they had also been referred to by the k-word. One pupil said a teacher had laughed off the question when asked why they called them monkeys. In response, Kwazi Mthethwa, KwaZulu-Natal Department of Education spokesperson, said the department was prepared to take action against those found guilty of racially victimising pupils. The school has been closed for the rest of the day. Daily News